post_text:
UPDATE ON FALL ATHLETICS from Superintendent Eastman:

After much discussion over the course of two different meetings, the Regional School Unit #24 Board of Directors voted unanimously to suspend interscholastic athletics for its students for the fall sports season. The Board is very aware of the importance of athletics to our students and our communities but felt that the safety of our students, staff, and school community is the top priority. The fluidity of the guidance being provided and the risk of the transmission of the Coronavirus in our schools through participation in athletics necessitated this decision.

(From Mr. Thurlow: we understand that many will want to comment on this post. As is the case with all posts, profanity, slander, threats, and/or harassment will not be tolerated)

post_text:
A Statement from Sumner Memorial High School:

It is part of our humanity to care deeply about our school, community, nation, and world. We are committed to creating an environment where people of all backgrounds feel safe, welcomed, and respected for who they are.

Our district policies support this commitment as Policy JIC states the following (the term ’students’ is synonymous for all in our Sumner Community): “Students should not discriminate against other people on the basis of race, color, sex, religion, ancestry, national origin, sexual orientation or disability. Nor should students harass anyone on the basis of race, color, sex, religion, ancestry, or national origin, sexual orientation or disability. Sexual harassment is also prohibited.”

In these uncertain times we encourage our school community to reach out to Sumner staff for open dialogue in our commitment to supporting all, and creating a safe environment for our community.

-Mr. Thurlow, Principal

post_text: On the eve of our return to our remote learning environment after a week of break we are compelled by true gratitude to highlight some often unsung heroes in our community. The Moshier's of 'YouNameIt' in Gouldsboro have been providing Sumner with amazing signage, gear, and school spirit resources for a number of years. Most recently, they helped us build upon our school year #SumnerStrong mantra in the form of signs for each and every student and staff member. (We have been seeing these in windows all over our district - hooray!) In your travels you may have noticed the newest addition to our front gym entrance - this is yet another wonderful design from the Moshier's: Entirely donated. Entirely unsolicited. Entirely awesome. Entirely wonderful. And entirely encompassing of the wonderful community spirit we enjoy here in Downeast Maine. So, to Klair, Scott, and Class of 2020 student Devin - we say THANK YOU for embodying and demonstrating the spirit of Sumner Memorial High School!!!

post_text:
Dear Sumner Community,

Please know that this update of not returning to the physical school building this year is jarring and disappointing for us all. But it is necessary for us all to stay safe and get ahead of this pandemic. I will be convening a stakeholder committee in the following days to discuss options for our graduation and end-of-year events. Please make no mistake, the Class of 2020 will be honored for all that they have achieved. My sincere hope is to hold graduation ceremonies sometime this Summer - pandemic willing. Please be patient while we work through many unknowns and obstacles over the next few weeks and months. Thank you for your continued support of all that is Sumner.

-Mr. Thurlow￼

post_text:
SUMNER REMOTE LEARNING UPDATE:

We are currently working to determine the most efficient ways to provide remote learning to our students. This work is complex with many factors and many moving pieces. IMPORTANT UPDATE FOR SCHOOL TOMORROW - STAFF ONLY DAY SATURDAY, MARCH 14, 2020 FOR ALL RSU 24 SCHOOLS

Dear RSU 24 Community,

We are continuing to monitor the COVID-19 situation that is impacting the country, our state, and events of all kinds. The health and well-being of our staff, students, and community is our number one priority. With that being said, tomorrow (Saturday) we will not be having students attend school as originally planned, and instead will be having a Staff-Only day at each building to discuss and make plans for the continuation of education in the event of a school closure.

We will continue to update you as information is made available to us. More information will be provided by Superintendent Eastman in the next couple of days. Thank you for your patience and understanding as we all work through this difficult time.

TIGERS IN THE THE NEWS:
This blurb appeared in an article titled "Top 10 Takes from the 2020 Maine Fishermen's Forum" in the National Fisherman:

Participants in the Eastern Maine Skippers Program held their own session to display their culminating projects. They included microplastics awareness, alternative lobster bait, new lobster trap design, and a solar-powered lobster boat.
The program is a supplemental and voluntary high school curriculum for young Mainers working in fisheries to provide the students with the core knowledge and skills to participate in co-managed fisheries, working with scientists and regulators to sustain the fisheries they depend upon as well as to run successful and adaptable businesses. The program is run by the Maine Center for Coastal Fisheries.

The Sumner Community has been experiencing some difficult times as of late. Our student body has been resilient and has been advocating for increased School Unity, School Pride, and Positive School Culture. Our staff, as always, has shown great care and concern for our students and for one another. This morning we gathered as a school and reviewed some action steps to define common goals and solutions to move us toward those goals. The most important part of these action steps are that we ALL work together, and that STUDENTS are a LARGE part of the solution. Additionally, we are looking for parents and community members who would like to be part of our collaborative efforts to determine solutions (if interested, please email me @ tthurlow@rsu24.org). The Sumner Community is strong, and although we struggle at times, we know that we can accomplish anything when we work together.

-Mr. Thurlow

Summer Job in Acadia National Park! See below, but for more details, come to guidance for a complete application package.

Acadia Youth Conservation Corps 2020- Job Announcement Acadia National Park, Bar Harbor, Maine
16 Positions Available
Application Period: 1/29/2020 – 3/30/2020
Acadia National Park is accepting applications for the seasonal Acadia Youth Conservation Corps (AYCC) to employ sixteen (16) teenagers to work on trails projects in Acadia National Park from June 22nd – August 14th, 2020. The United States Youth Conservation Corps (YCC) is a summer youth employment program that engages young people in meaningful work experiences on national parks, forests, wildlife refuges, and fish hatcheries while developing an ethic of environmental stewardship and civic responsibility. The efforts of AYCC contribute greatly to the outstanding condition of Acadia National Park’s trails and carriage roads.

CONGRATULATIONS TO OUR SUMNER CHEERING TEAM!!!

2020 CLASS C Northern Maine CHAMPIONS!!!!!

post_text:
CHEERING COMPETITION BACK ON!

Much to our surprise, and good fortune, this morning has brought us a weather model and weather forecast that WILL ALLOW US THE OPPORTUNITY TO PARTICIPATE IN THE DAC CHEERING CHAMPIONSHIPS tonight at 6:00PM. Although the weather still calls for lots of precipitation in the form of rain, we feel confident that it will now be safe for our team, coaches, and families to travel to Woodland High School and back. As always, we ask that students, families, and community members making this trip exercise extra caution. We hope to see a great turnout for this competition, Go Tigers!

On a side note - all other athletic events (Wrestling, Indoor Track, & Basketball) are still being held as originally scheduled.

-Mr. Thurlow

post_text: On Tuesday, Sumner's Eastern Maine Skippers Class visited the State House, met with Governor Janet Mills, and had the opportunity to talk with Representative McDonald (Stonington) of the Marine Resources Committee. Afterward they spent time at the Department of Marine Resources, where they met with the Commissioner and Captain of the Marine Patrol and discussed the future of Maine's fisheries.
text: On Tuesday, Sumner's Eastern Maine Skippers Class visited the State House, met with Governor Janet Mills, and had the opportunity to talk with Representative McDonald (Stonington) of the Marine Resources Committee. Afterward they spent time at the Department of Marine Resources, where they met with the Commissioner and Captain of the Marine Patrol and discussed the future of Maine's fisheries.

We will be holding school on Saturday, February 29th (half day) and Saturday, March 14th (half day). In addition to these Saturday half days, during the week of March 23rd-March 27th we will be adding an extra hour each day for students (Mon-Thurs. students will be dismissed at 3:30PM, and Friday students will be dismissed at 2:30PM

We are planning creatively for these changes in the school calendar. We will be sending out a bell schedule for these changes before we leave for February Break.

post_text:
On Saturday, November 9, JMG students visited Our Furry Husky Kiddos, a husky rescue and sled dog training facility in Ellsworth.

Students had the opportunity to bond with over a dozen husky sled dogs. Training sessions were provided around sled racing, differences with the dogs due to age and experience, genetic characteristics, and relocation for dogs looking for forever homes.

Students are very excited for return visits, and look forward to providing on-going, continued support for this amazing community resource.

post_text: Next week our students will be taking a yearly Gallup Poll that helps Sumner better support our students. The poll takes ten minutes to complete and students will take the poll (individually and anonymously during) during Tiger Time on October 17th and/or October 18th. The letter (pictured here) will be sent home tomorrow/Friday with your student. In the past we have had nearly 100% student participation. If for some reason you do not wish for your student to participate please sign the bottom of the letter and return it to school by Thursday morning, October 17th. Thank you!
